The subst-ref bug survived because the corpus was inherited from
upstream kati, which SHARES such bugs — its own testcases never probe
them. This adds a systematic sweep, one probe file per syntax family
with adversarial inputs, each diffed against real GNU make by the
hard gate: text functions, filename functions, computed names /
value/origin/flavor, call/foreach/if/or/and, define flavors,
conditional forms, target- and pattern-specific vars, double-colon +
static patterns, automatic vars (D/F, ^ vs +, |), the vpath
directive, special vars, export/unexport/undefine.

8/12 matched GNU immediately. The sweep caught three more real bugs,
fixed here:
- $(call) did not set $(0) to the function name.
- $* was empty in EXPLICIT rules; GNU sets it to the target minus a
  known suffix (.SUFFIXES, default list from GNU's default.c) —
  modeled as a %suffix output pattern so the stem logic is shared.
- the vpath DIRECTIVE was a parse error ('missing separator'); now a
  real statement (VpathStmt) feeding pattern-scoped entries into the
  dependency search, with GNU's clear-one/clear-all forms. Upstream's
  vpath_directive.mk TODO now passes and its marker is dropped.

Remaining known gap, visibly TODO'd (not silently skipped):
double-colon parts must be independent dep nodes (per-part prereqs +
declaration-order execution); kati merges them into one node.

rkati corpus 387/397 fail=0 xpass=0; box corpus 387/397 fail=0.

